## 5. Potential Sources of Standards

To populate the global standards library:

- Open Source repositories with permissive licenses (MIT, Apache, GPL)
- Open projects like VS Code (Electron-based editors)
- Standard libraries of programming languages
- Voluntary contributions from developers and companies
- Pattern analysis from public GitHub repositories

### 5.1. Why Code Owners Will Contribute for Free

Code owners can voluntarily contribute frameworks (without unique business logic) to standardization, receiving access to the same system for their own development in return.

This is mutually beneficial:
- Microsoft contributes VS Code framework → uses others' frameworks for other projects
- Google contributes Chrome framework → uses others' frameworks
- Everyone wins

Unique logic stays with the owner. Framework goes to the standard.

### 5.2. Collective Building

Imagine: thousands of people building the database, creating unique keys, writing code using these keys. Each contribution strengthens the system. Want to add to the database — go ahead. And you use everything that's there.

